    <body><div type="letter">
      <p>[letter ends on page 4 with no closing]</p>
      <p>Sweet Mate. The Avis had yesterday a confirmed cold, so has not been out since Friday. I am not sorry that Dr Locock should have this opportunity of seeing what my colds are like, though this one is by no means one of my worst.-- In other</p>
      <p>respects I am doing well, &amp; the pain I had on Friday can be I am told properly accounted for, &amp; is not likely to return. It seems now Dr L's opinion &amp; hope that there may be no more trouble of any kind, or prospect of little birdies, for months to come.--</p>
      <p>Mrs Clermont who was a long time with the baby yesterday, &amp; you know was with Mama</p>
      <p>at her birth &amp;, first months of existence, thinks this one extremely unlike her, &amp; especially in the eyes, which she says must turn decidedly black like Byron's.--</p>
      <p>Mama was a very quiet infant &amp; rarely cried at all. I squalled almost incessantly for 6 weeks, so in this my daughter is no Ada &amp; no Annabella.--</p>
      <p>I find so much to do that I almost think</p>
      <p>me may have to delay going, till Friday or Saturday.-- This can be left undecided however at present, &amp; I shall do as you may wish about it.--</p>
      <p>No answer from Mr Madge. Stephen says you did not desire one to be asked for.--</p>
      <p>I was so pleased this morning with ou sweet letter all about flowers.</p>
    </div></body>
